I will explain: This rhodo did what rhodos and many other shrubs do a lot of, and it is one way that they spread themselves around in nature. Where leaf nodes of old lower branches touch the ground, they spontaneously produce roots. Gardeners can encourage this behaviour in woody shrubs they want to propagate (a technique known as layering), by lightly nicking the hard outer tissue of a low-growing branch just below a leaf node and pegging it down into a bit of compost-improved soil. Within a season the branch will have produced some small roots. Before it is ready to be potted up, however (and this is where the above little rooty scrap may come a cropper), the branch should be severed from its "parent" and left undisturbed for a few more months while it makes its own fully independent root system.
